            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What are health metrics and why do they matter?</h2>
              <p>
                Health metrics are measurable numbers that reflect aspects of
                your health: body composition, cardiovascular fitness, metabolic
                rate, and more. Professional organizations and large research
                projects use similar indicators to track population health. At
                an individual level, they help you understand where you are
                today and how lifestyle changes are affecting you over time.
              </p>
              <p>
                This dashboard brings together several of the most commonly
                recommended personal health metrics in one place, using
                transparent formulas and clear interpretation ranges.
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas used in this health metrics dashboard</h2>

              <h3>1. Body Mass Index (BMI)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Metric units:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMI} = \dfrac{\text{weight (kg)}}{\text{height
                  (m)}^2}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Imperial units (lb, in):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMI} = \dfrac{\text{weight (lb)} \times
                  703}{\text{height (in)}^2}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Typical adult BMI categories:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>&lt; 18.5 – Underweight</li>
                <li>18.5–24.9 – Normal weight</li>
                <li>25.0–29.9 – Overweight</li>
                <li>≥ 30.0 – Obesity (class I, II, III depending on level)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                BMI is a simple screening tool and does not distinguish between
                fat and muscle. That is why this dashboard also estimates body
                fat and uses waist measurements.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Body fat percentage (U.S. Navy method)</h3>
              <p>
                The U.S. Navy circumference method is a widely used field
                estimate of body fat percentage based on simple tape
                measurements. It is not as accurate as DEXA or other imaging,
                but it is practical for home use.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>For men:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\%\text{Body fat} = 495 / (1.0324 - 0.19077
                  \log_{10}(\text{waist} - \text{neck}) + 0.15456
                  \log_{10}(\text{height})) - 450\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>For women:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\%\text{Body fat} = 495 / (1.29579 - 0.35004
                  \log_{10}(\text{waist} + \text{hip} - \text{neck}) + 0.22100
                  \log_{10}(\text{height})) - 450\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In this simplified version we approximate neck circumference
                from height and sex when it is not provided, which introduces
                additional uncertainty. Treat the result as a rough estimate,
                not a diagnostic value.
              </p>

              <h3>
                3. Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR) and Total Daily Energy Expenditure
                (TDEE)
              </h3>
              <p>
                BMR is the energy your body uses at rest. We use the Mifflin–St
                Jeor equation, which is commonly recommended for adults.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>For men:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height (cm)} - 5 \times \text{age (years)} + 5\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>For women:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height (cm)} - 5 \times \text{age (years)} - 161\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                To estimate your
                <strong>Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE)</strong>, we
                multiply BMR by an activity factor:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Sedentary: 1.2</li>
                <li>Lightly active: 1.375</li>
                <li>Moderately active: 1.55</li>
                <li>Very active: 1.725</li>
                <li>Athlete / physical job: 1.9</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Heart rate metrics</h3>
              <p>
                We use simple, widely used formulas for maximum and target heart
                rate zones.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Maximum heart rate:</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{HR}_{\max} \approx 220 - \text{age (years)}\)</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Moderate–vigorous target zone:</strong>
                </p>
                <p>50–85% of \(\text{HR}_{\max}\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Resting heart rate is entered by you. For most healthy adults, a
                resting heart rate between about 60 and 100 bpm is considered
                typical, though trained athletes may have lower values.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Waist-to-hip ratio (WHR)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{WHR} = \dfrac{\text{waist circumference}}{\text{hip
                  circumference}}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Higher WHR indicates more abdominal fat. Typical risk thresholds
                often used:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Men: WHR &gt; 0.90 – increased cardiometabolic risk</li>
                <li>Women: WHR &gt; 0.85 – increased cardiometabolic risk</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>6. Blood pressure categories (informal)</h3>
              <p>
                Blood pressure categories vary slightly between guidelines. This
                tool uses common cut‑offs for adults to label your self‑reported
                reading:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Normal: &lt; 120 / &lt; 80 mmHg</li>
                <li>Elevated: 120–129 / &lt; 80 mmHg</li>
                <li>High (Stage 1): 130–139 / 80–89 mmHg</li>
                <li>High (Stage 2): ≥ 140 / ≥ 90 mmHg</li>
                <li>
                  Hypertensive crisis: ≥ 180 / ≥ 120 mmHg (seek urgent care)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always confirm blood pressure concerns with a clinician using
                proper equipment and multiple readings.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use this dashboard effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measure consistently.</strong> Use the same scale,
                  tape measure, and time of day when possible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Track trends, not single numbers.</strong> Small
                  day‑to‑day fluctuations are normal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Combine metrics.</strong> For example, a slightly high
                  BMI with a small waist and good fitness may be less concerning
                  than BMI alone suggests.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use metrics to guide habits.</strong> Pair your
                  numbers with sustainable changes in sleep, movement,
                  nutrition, and stress management.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Partner with your clinician.</strong> Share your
                  trends during check‑ups for personalized interpretation.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and safety</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Formulas are based on population averages and may be less
                  accurate for some ethnicities, ages, and body types.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Body fat and energy needs are estimates, not precise
                  measurements.
                </li>
                <li>
                  This tool is not suitable for pregnancy, serious illness, or
                  children without professional guidance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you have symptoms such as chest pain, severe shortness of
                  breath, fainting, or very high readings, seek urgent medical
                  care.
                </li>
              </ul>
