                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Which health metrics are most important to track?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For most adults, the most useful metrics to track at home
                    are weight and BMI, waist circumference or waist‑to‑hip
                    ratio, resting heart rate, blood pressure, estimated body
                    fat percentage, and basic activity levels (steps or exercise
                    minutes). Together they give a broad picture of
                    cardiometabolic health and fitness.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How often should I check my health metrics?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Weekly for weight and resting heart rate, monthly for waist
                    and body fat, and at least a few times per year for blood
                    pressure if you are otherwise healthy. If you already have
                    high blood pressure, diabetes, or heart disease, follow your
                    clinician’s monitoring plan.
                  </p>
